    "His first significant show on Byzantine art was mounted the same year.": [],
    "Beckwith, by his own admission, matured at the Museum through the collegial exchange with other V&A scholars, both senior and junior, who, in addition to Pope-Hennessy, included <a href=\"/hodgkinsont\">Terence Hodgkinson</a>, and <a href=\"/baxandallm\">Michael Baxandall</a>.": [],
    "Taking inspiration from the former V&A director, <a href=\"/ashtonl\">Leigh Ashton</a>, he brought new, visually appealing exhibition techniques to the Museum.": [],
    "Beckwith's ability to summarize art history led to the commissioning of one in the second set of commissions of the Pelican History of Art series (begun in the 1950s) under the direction of <a href=\"/pevsnern\">Nikolaus Bernard Leon Pevsner</a>.": [],
    "<em>Early Christian and Byzantine Art</em>, first issued in 1970, brought him a wider international audience.": [],
    "The sumptuous <em>Ivory Carvings in Early Medieval England</em> in 1972 remains his most important original work of scholarship.": [],
    "At the suggestion of the art historian (and Museum advisory board member) <a href=\"/clarkk\">Kenneth Clark</a>, it became an exhibition at the Victorian and Albert.": [],
    "In 1974 Beckwith was named Keeper, succeeding Hodgkinson.": [
